<exercise xml:id="qs-trans">
    <title>Translating Center of Figure</title>

    <introduction>
        <p>
            In this exercise, we will look at a few different surfaces and the algebraic forms used to translate the center or key feature of the surface. In particular, we will look at spheres, cones, and a parabolic cylinder surface with translations away from the origin.
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                For this part, we will be looking at transformations of the sphere given by <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m>. 
            </p>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        We need to start with a description of the key features of our surface. For a sphere, you need to state the center and radius since the surface is going to be complete described by these two features. Write a sentence that gives the center and radius for the sphere given by <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The sphere given by <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m> will have center at the origin and radius 1.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Write a sentence that gives the center and radius for the sphere given by <m>(x-2)^2+y^2+z^2=1</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The sphere given by <m>(x-2)^2+y^2+z^2=1</m> will have center at <m>(2,0,0)</m> and radius 1.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Give the equation for a sphere with center <m>(-4,2,-3)</m> and radius 1.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>(x+4)^2+(y-2)^2+(z+3)^2=1</m>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Generalize your work to give the equation of a sphere of radius 1 with center <m>(x_0,y_0,z_0)</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>(x-x_0)^2+(y-y_0)^2+(z-z_0)^2=1</m>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                For this part, we will be looking at transformations of the cone given by <m>x^2+y^2=z^2</m>. 
            </p>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        We need to start with a description of the key features of our surface. For a cone, you need to state the center (where the vertex of the cone occurs) and the axis of symmetry that the cone is centered on, since the cone is going to be complete described by these two features. Write a sentence that gives the center and axis of symmetry for the cone given by <m>x^2+y^2=z^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The cone given by <m>x^2+y^2=z^2</m> will have its center/vertex at the origin and will have an axis of symmetry of the z-axis.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Write a sentence that gives the center and axis of symmetry for the cone given by <m>(x)^2+(y-2)^2=(z+1)^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The cone given by <m>(x)^2+(y-2)^2=(z+1)^2</m> will have center/vertex at <m>(0,2,-1)</m> and will have a axis of symmetry parallel to the z-axis.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Give the equation for a cone with axis of symmetry along the x-axis and center at the origin.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <hint>
                    <p>
                        Switch the roles of <m>x</m> and <m>z</m>.
                    </p>
                </hint>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The equation of a cone with axis of symmetry along the x-axis and center at the origin will be <m>y^2+z^2=x^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Give the equation for a cone with axis of symmetry along the y-axis and center at <m>(1,-3,2)</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The equation for a cone with axis of symmetry along the y-axis and center at <m>(1,-3,2)</m> will be given by <m>(x-1)^2+(z-2)^2=(y+3)^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Generalize your work to give the equation of cone with axis of symmetry along the x-axis and center at <m>(x_0,y_0,z_0)</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The equation of cone with axis of symmetry along the x-axis and center at <m>(x_0,y_0,z_0)</m> will be <m>(y-y_0)^2+(z-z_0)^2=(x-x_0)^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </statement>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                For this part, we will be looking at transformations of the parabolic cylinder given by <m>x^2=y</m>. 
            </p>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        We need to start with a description of the key features of our surface. For a parabolic cylinder surface, you need to state the plane with the generating curve and the features of the generating curve, since the surface is going to be complete described by these two features. Write a couple of sentences to describe this cylinder surface given by <m>y=x^2</m>. Be sure to include which plane contains the generating curve and the important features of the generating curve. You should also state which axis the rulings will be parallel to. 
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The cylinder surface given by <m>y=x^2</m> will have a generating curve given by a parabola in the <m>xy</m>-plane. The generating parabola will have its vertex at the origin of the <m>xy</m>-plane and will extend in the positive y direction. The rulings of this surface will be parallel to the z axis.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Write a couple of sentences to describe the parabolic cylinder given by <m>-(y+1)=(x-2)^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The cylinder surface given by <m>-(y+1)=(x-2)^2</m> will have a generating curve given by a parabola in the <m>xy</m>-plane. The generating parabola will have its vertex at the point <m>(2,-1)</m> of the <m>xy</m>-plane and will extend in the positive y direction. The rulings of this surface will be parallel to the z-axis.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Write a couple of sentences to describe the parabolic cylinder given by <m>(x+3)=(z-1)^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The cylinder surface given by <m>(x+3)=(z-1)^2</m> will have a generating curve given by a parabola in the <m>xz</m>-plane. The generating parabola will have its vertex at the point <m>(-3,1)</m> of the <m>xz</m>-plane and will extend in the positive x direction. The rulings of this surface will be parallel to the y-axis.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Give the equation for a parabolic cylinder surface with generating curve in the yz-plane, with vertex of the generating parabola at <m>(0,-2,4)</m>, and parabola extending in the negative z direction. 
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The equation for a parabolic cylinder surface with generating curve in the yz-plane, with vertex of the generating parabola at <m>(0,-2,4)</m>, and parabola extending in the negative z direction is given by <m>-(z-4)=(y+2)^2</m>.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </statement>
    </task>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="qs-stretch">
<introduction>
    <p>
        In this exercise, we will look at how stretches of each coordinate direction appear algebraically as a transformation of our quadric and cylinder surfaces. 
    </p>
</introduction>
<task>
    <statement>
        <p>
            In this part, we will look at coordinate stretching/shrinking being applied to a sphere. 
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        For the sphere given by <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m>, describe how the surface is stretched (relative to the center) in each of the coordinate directions. 
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The sphere given by <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=1</m> is stretched one away from the center in every direction. 
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        For the sphere given by <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=16</m>, describe how the surface is stretched (relative to the center) in each of the coordinate directions.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The sphere given by <m>x^2+y^2+z^2=16</m> is stretched four away from the center (at the origin) in every direction. 
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        What kind of surface is given by <m>\frac{x^2}{9}+\frac{y^2}{4}+z^2=1</m>. Give the shape of the surface and how it is stretched relative to the basic sphere in the previous task.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        The surface is given by <m>\frac{x^2}{9}+\frac{y^2}{4}+z^2=1</m> is an ellipsoid centered at the origin and has been stretched by a factor of 3 parallel to the x-axis, by a factor of 2 parallel to the y-direction, and by a factor of 1 parallel to the z-direction.
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Give the equation of an ellipsoid with center <m>(1,2,3)</m> that has been stretched by a by a factor of 6 parallel to the x-axis, by a factor of 2/3 parallel to the y-direction, and by a factor of <m>\pi</m> parallel to the z-direction.
                    </p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <m>\frac{(x-1)^2}{36}+\frac{(y-2)^2}{\frac{4}{9}}+\frac{(z-3)^2}{\pi^2}=1</m>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </task>
        </p>
    </statement>
</task>
<task>
    <statement>
        <p>
            In this part of the exercise, we will look at coordinate stretching/shrinking being applied to a hyperboloid of one-sheet. 
        </p>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For the hyperboloid of one-sheet given by <m>x^2+y^2-z^2=1</m>, describe how the surface is stretched (relative to the center) in each of the coordinate directions. You should also give the coordinate axis that describes the axis of symmetry/rotation for this hyperboloid.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The hyperboloid of one-sheet given by <m>x^2+y^2-z^2=1</m> is stretched one away from the center the origin in the xy-plane. The axis of symmetry/rotation is the z-axis because this surface is centered on the z-axis.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                  For the hyperboloid of one-sheet given by <m>\frac{x^2}{9}+\frac{y^2}{4}-z^2=1</m>, describe how the surface is stretched (relative to the center) in each of the coordinate directions. You should also give the coordinate axis that describes the axis of symmetry/rotation for this hyperboloid.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The hyperboloid of one-sheet given by <m>\frac{x^2}{9}+\frac{y^2}{4}-z^2=1</m> is stretched by a factor of three parallel to the x-axis and by a factor of two parallel to the y axis. The axis of symmetry/rotation is the z-axis because this surface is centered on the z-axis.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Give the equation of a hyperboloid of one sheet centered on the y-axis that has been stretched by a factor of five parallel to the x-axis and by a factor of <m>\frac{6}{7}</m> parallel to the z-axis.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <m>\frac{x^2}{25}+\frac{z^2}{\frac{36}{49}}-y^2=1</m>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    How would the description of the surface given by <m>\frac{(x-2)^2}{25}+\frac{(z-\pi)^2}{\frac{36}{49}}-\frac{y^2}{4}=1</m> be different than the surface from the previous task
                </p>
            </statement>
            <hint>
                <p>
                    Make sure you look at where the axis of symmetry/rotation will be.
                </p>
            </hint>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The surface given by <m>\frac{(x-2)^2}{25}+\frac{(z-\pi)^2}{\frac{36}{49}}-\frac{y^2}{4}=1</m> will be centered on the line parallel to the y-axis through the point <m>(2,0,\pi)</m>. Additionally, he surface given by <m>\frac{(x-2)^2}{25}+\frac{(z-\pi)^2}{\frac{36}{49}}-\frac{y^2}{4}=1</m> will be strectched by a factor of two parallel to the y-axis.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </task>
    </statement>
</task>
</exercise>





 

