<!-- The question below should probably go later, like in the common graphs section-->
<exercise label="Library__FortLewis__Calc3__12-1-Two-variable-functions__HGM4-12-1-28-Functions-of-two-variables__pg" xml:id="ex-9-1-WW-Matching-distances">
  <!--<title>Matching distances</title>-->
   <webwork source="Library/FortLewis/Calc3/12-1-Two-variable-functions/HGM4-12-1-28-Functions-of-two-variables.pg"/>
</exercise>

<exercise>
    <introduction>
        <p>
            Using your newly found understanding of cylinder and quadric surfaces, for each equation given below, write a couple sentences to describe the shape and key features of each surface. You should try to draw a good plot of each equation by hand and label your graphs. 
        </p>
    </introduction>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>25x^2+4y^2+100z^2=100</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The surface given by <m>25x^2+4y^2+100z^2=100</m> is an ellipsoid. Reformatting this algebraically, we get <m>\frac{x^2}{4}+\frac{y^2}{25}+z^2=1</m>, which shows a stretch of 2 in the x-direction, 5 in the y-direction, and 1 in the z-direction.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>25x^2+4y^2-100z^2=100</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The surface given by <m>25x^2+4y^2-100z^2=100</m> is a hyperboloid of one sheet. Reformatting this algebraically, we get <m>\frac{x^2}{4}+\frac{y^2}{25}-z^2=1</m>, which shows a stretch of 2 in the x-direction, 5 in the y-direction, and 1 in the z-direction. Additionally, we see the hyperboloid centered on the z-axis.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
               <m>-25x^2-4y^2+100z^2=100</m> 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The surface given by <m>-25x^2-4y^2+100z^2=100</m> is a hyperboloid of two sheets. Reformatting this algebraically, we get <m>-\frac{x^2}{4}-\frac{y^2}{25}+z^2=1</m>, which shows a stretch of 2 in the x-direction, 5 in the y-direction, and 1 in the z-direction. Additionally, we see the hyperboloid of two sheets centered on the z-axis, but this means there is a gap between the two sheets from -1 to 1 on the z-axis.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>25x^2-4y^2=0</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The surface given by <m>25x^2-4y^2=0</m> will a cylinder surface generated by two lines intersecting at the origin with generating curve in the xy-plane and rulings parallel to the z-axis. The generating lines will be given by <m>y=\pm \frac{5}{2}x</m>. This could also be described by the two intersecting planes given by <m>y=\pm \frac{5}{2}x</m>. The generating curve for this cylinder surface is created by a degenerate form of a hyperbola since the right side of the equation is zero instead of 1.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>25x^2+4y^2+100z^2=0</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The surface given by <m>25x^2+4y^2+100z^2=0</m> will be a point. The only point that will satisfy this equation is the origin.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>25x^2+4y^2+100z=0</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The surface given by <m>25x^2+4y^2+100z=0</m> will be an elliptic paraboloid. Solving for z as a function of x and y gives <m>z=-\frac{x^2}{4}-\frac{y^2}{25}</m>. The elliptic paraboloid will have a vertex at the origin and open toward the negative z-axis. Additionally, this paraboloid will be stretched by a factor of 2 in the x-direction and by a factor of 5 in the y-direction. 
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
               <m>25x^2-4y^2+100z=0</m> 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The surface given by <m>25x^2-4y^2+100z=0</m> will be a hyperbolic paraboloid (saddle). Solving for z as a function of x and y gives <m>z=-\frac{x^2}{4}+\frac{y^2}{25}</m>. The saddle point of the surface will be at the origin. The surface will consist of upward facing (positive z-direction) parabolas in directions parallel to the x axis and downward facing (negative z-direction) parabolas in directions parallel to the y-axis.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>-4y^2+100z=0</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The surface given by <m>-4y^2+100z=0</m> will be a parabolic cylinder surface. The generating curve will be given by a parabola in the yz-plane with vertex at the origin and opening toward the positive z-axis with rulings parallel to the x-axis. 
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
               <m>25x+4y+100z=100</m> 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The surface given by <m>25x+4y+100z=100</m> will be a plane. This plane has intercepts <m>(4,0,0),(0,25,0),(0,0,1)</m>. 
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>-25x^2-4y^2-100z^2=100</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The surface given by <m>-25x^2-4y^2-100z^2=100</m> will be an empty set. There are no points that satisfy <m>-25x^2-4y^2-100z^2=100</m> because the left hand side will always be zero or less. 
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>25x^2-4y^2+100z^2=-100</m>   
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The surface given by <m>25x^2-4y^2+100z^2=-100</m> will be a hyperboloid of one sheet centered on the y-axis. We can reorganize this algebraically to get <m>-\frac{x^2}{4}+\frac{y^2}{25}-z^2=1</m>. This surface has been stretched by a factor of two in the x-direction and 5 in the y-direction.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </task>   
</exercise>
